{"id":"263061932_The_Causal_Relevance_of_Content_to_Computation","abstract":"Many philosophers worry that the classical computational theory of mind (CTM) engenders epiphenomenalism. Building on Block’s (1990) discussion, I formulate a particularly troubling version of this worry. I then present a novel solution to CTM’s epiphenomenalist conundrum. I develop my solution within an interventionist theory of causal relevance. My solution departs substantially from orthodox versions of CTM. In particular, I reject the widespread picture of digital computation as formal syntactic manipulation.","authors":["Michael Rescorla"],"meta":["January 2014Philosophy and Phenomenological Research 88(1)","DOI:10.1111/j.1933-1592.2012.00619.x"],"references":["286207332_Epiphenomenalism_Thinking_about_causes_From_Greek_philosophy_to_modern_physics","242448131_Causation_Prediction_and_Search","228018371_Wide_Causation","30530201_Non-Reductive_Physicalism_and_the_Limits_of_the_Exclusion_Principle","329654602_Causation_Prediction_and_Search","329652982_Psychosemantics_The_Problem_of_Meaning_in_the_Philosophy_of_Mind","324343879_A_Theory_of_Content_and_Other_Essays","313097840_Minds_brains_and_programs","304344058_Minds_brains_and_programs_The_Behavioral_and_Brain_Sciences_vol","287597720_Physicalism_Or_Something_Near_Enough","285174687_How_to_Integrate_Representation_into_Computational_Modeling_and_Why_We_Should","273364770_Artificial_Intelligence_The_Very_Idea","273071647_The_Elm_and_the_Expert","272160113_Minds_Brains_and_Programs","270420135_Physicalism_or_Something_Near_Enough","270201612_A_Theory_of_Content_and_Other_Essays","269858824_Representations_Targets_and_Attitudes","266596289_Memory_and_The_Computational_Brain_Why_Cognitive_Science_Will_Transform_Neuroscience","261743680_Causation_as_Influence","252127934_A_Modest_Role_for_Content_Draft","249882262_Contrastive_Causation","248526463_Computational_models_A_modest_role_for_content","246751060_Making_Things_Happen_A_Theory_of_C